1
00:00:00,723 --> 00:00:19,795
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambuddhasa

2
00:00:20,533 --> 00:00:34,377
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:39,405 --> 00:00:44,533
So I just thought this evening we might approach daily life a bit.

4
00:00:45,323 --> 00:01:15,060
in terms of in our practice and I looked up two words here in the great Oxford dictionary the contrast between impulsive and spontaneous it's interesting how close the definitions come so it says impulsive is an action done without thought and spontaneous spontaneity is performed or occurring as a result of a sudden impulse

5
00:01:17,587 --> 00:01:20,134
Not much difference there, is there?

6
00:01:20,153 --> 00:01:23,400
Inclination without premeditation of one's...

7
00:01:23,421 --> 00:01:26,927
It's interesting that the word impulse comes from the Latin, which means driven on.

8
00:01:28,290 --> 00:01:32,661
But the spontaneous comes from the Latin, which means of one's own accord.

9
00:01:33,281 --> 00:01:35,344
It gives it a slightly different.

10
00:01:35,364 --> 00:01:40,632
But definitely in our use of these two words, impulsive is seen as something not very good.

11
00:01:41,233 --> 00:01:43,296
And spontaneous is exactly how we want to be.

12
00:01:44,457 --> 00:01:46,159
To live a spontaneous life.

13
00:01:46,281 --> 00:01:48,183
Everybody wants to be spontaneous.

14
00:01:49,685 --> 00:01:56,454
And I think the added understanding of spontaneous is that you're very happy.

15
00:01:56,721 --> 00:01:58,006
Don't you think?

16
00:01:58,025 --> 00:02:05,466
You know, you're spontaneous and happy, impulsive and wicked and silly, you know, reckless.

17
00:02:06,549 --> 00:02:11,203
So these two words are very close together and it's...

18
00:02:12,044 --> 00:02:15,149
We've just got to look at these parami.

19
00:02:15,169 --> 00:02:16,931
So parami means the other shore.

20
00:02:16,991 --> 00:02:19,675
So it's translated as perfection.

21
00:02:20,455 --> 00:02:24,442
But it just means really those virtues that take you to the other shore.

22
00:02:24,983 --> 00:02:28,207
And that's the Buddha's image for Nibbana.

23
00:02:28,228 --> 00:02:29,188
It's the other shore.

24
00:02:29,830 --> 00:02:35,318
And the sea he uses often as a metaphor for the journey.

25
00:02:37,777 --> 00:02:44,210
He talks about those who've not achieved Sotapanna, the first instance, as swimming under the water.

26
00:02:45,372 --> 00:02:47,235
Don't know where they're going.

27
00:02:47,254 --> 00:02:51,141
And the stream entrant, their head is bobbing up and down.

28
00:02:52,084 --> 00:02:55,088
So they sort of generally know where they're going.

29
00:02:55,109 --> 00:02:55,811
Oh, no, that's right.

30
00:02:55,830 --> 00:02:58,215
No, the stream entrant, his head's above water.

31
00:02:58,575 --> 00:03:02,081
So at least he sees or she sees where they're going.

32
00:03:02,686 --> 00:03:09,831
The Sakudagami, the one who is a once-returner, is swimming vigorously towards the shore.

33
00:03:10,552 --> 00:03:13,936
And the Anagami, the non-returner, is actually standing on the shore.

34
00:03:14,295 --> 00:03:16,858
So they've actually in some sense reached the end of the path.

35
00:03:17,639 --> 00:03:23,804
And then of course there's the path towards the middle of the island, and that's the attainment of full liberation.

36
00:03:23,824 --> 00:03:31,730
So the idea of the other shore is one way of the Buddha sort of pointing that these virtues are needed.

37
00:03:33,009 --> 00:03:50,711
And if we take that trilogy of generosity, well, gratitude actually isn't one of these, pardon me, but generosity is, and renunciation.

38
00:03:52,354 --> 00:03:59,322
When we're generous impulsively, when we give impulsively,

39
00:03:59,503 --> 00:04:00,465
or even recklessly.

40
00:04:00,786 --> 00:04:04,129
Or when we help somebody, somebody says, you know, can you help me decorate?

41
00:04:05,191 --> 00:04:13,901
And when you say yes in that sort of impulsive way, there's always that aftermath of, oh, God, do I really want to do that?

42
00:04:13,921 --> 00:04:18,608
And then you're trying to work out some way of getting out of it.

43
00:04:18,648 --> 00:04:22,872
And at the time when they expect you to come, you've mysteriously fallen ill.

44
00:04:25,596 --> 00:04:27,738
Disappeared down to the beach or something.

45
00:04:27,718 --> 00:04:44,096
So that sort of impulsive action, if we stop, if we can just stop that, and it's very difficult, of course, when you're in action, when somebody comes and says, you know, can you help me?

46
00:04:44,115 --> 00:04:44,737
Can you do this?

47
00:04:45,276 --> 00:04:49,841
It's very difficult to just stop and say, no, I won't.

48
00:04:50,262 --> 00:04:56,629
But I think we can give ourselves a bit of time by saying, oh, well, I'll have to look at my diary or I'll think about it or whatever.

49
00:04:56,608 --> 00:04:57,692
Just give me a moment.

50
00:04:58,452 --> 00:05:06,291
So you have to give yourself a bit of space to not to fall into that sort of impulsive way of doing things.

51
00:05:06,312 --> 00:05:08,677
And of course when you

52
00:05:10,091 --> 00:05:29,704
If you do something like that, if you decide to do something impulsively, and then you sort of sit with those feelings, rather than letting them take you over, you know, the feeling of self-annoyance and annoyance with the person for asking you and all that sort of stuff, if you sit with those feelings,

53
00:05:29,684 --> 00:05:38,324
and you let them pass, then perhaps the underlying motivations come up, the ones that are impulsive and driving you on.

54
00:05:38,564 --> 00:05:40,329
I mean, that's where the impulse is coming from.

55
00:05:40,408 --> 00:05:43,276
It's coming from some underlying conditioning.

56
00:05:43,295 --> 00:05:45,701
It may be that you're afraid to lose friendship.

57
00:05:45,682 --> 00:05:53,995
It may be that it's one way of not feeling lonely that you go and help somebody occasionally.

58
00:05:54,495 --> 00:06:01,547
I mean there might be all sorts of reasons, murky reasons underneath which is making us act in these impulsive ways.

59
00:06:02,894 --> 00:06:06,358
I mean, this is something that people like Freud understood very well.

60
00:06:07,060 --> 00:06:09,283
But it comes out if you give it time.

61
00:06:09,382 --> 00:06:10,024
This is the point.

62
00:06:10,103 --> 00:06:18,415
It comes out if you allow the negativity that comes up to just pass away and then just see what comes up.

63
00:06:18,476 --> 00:06:20,379
I mean, if nothing comes up, nothing comes up.

64
00:06:20,399 --> 00:06:32,596
But something may just come up which manifests to you what's actually making you make these impulsive decisions.

65
00:06:36,644 --> 00:06:39,367
So how do we become spontaneous?

66
00:06:39,387 --> 00:06:43,151
I mean, how do we undermine that and become spontaneous?

67
00:06:43,492 --> 00:06:48,918
Well, the sort of underlying understanding of spontaneity is that it is virtuous.

68
00:06:49,920 --> 00:07:05,317
So absolute spontaneity won't arise until, in a sense, we're fully liberated in that sort of total way, because there'll always be some murky little nasty reason for doing something which is driving us on, even unknowingly.

69
00:07:05,872 --> 00:07:33,009
But even so, even if that's there, we can still develop that virtuous habit, that virtuous conditioning, which allows us to act spontaneously in that virtuous way, and it brings more happiness than a feeling of compulsion, of being compelled to do something.

70
00:07:34,204 --> 00:07:39,639
And that's where we get a bit confused because I think we think that spontaneity ought to arise spontaneously.

71
00:07:40,382 --> 00:07:44,273
You know, like you wake up one morning and, yeah, everything's spontaneous, you know.

72
00:07:44,293 --> 00:07:49,648
I just woke up and had an egg and everything happened spontaneously, you know.

73
00:07:50,675 --> 00:07:55,161
But spontaneity only comes with practice, with actual training.

74
00:07:55,882 --> 00:08:00,668
And I think I mentioned this one of the days.

75
00:08:00,887 --> 00:08:14,185
If we look at people like concert performers, pianists, violinists, people like that, and sports people, I think these two manifest what we mean by spontaneity.

76
00:08:14,704 --> 00:08:26,317
and we know that an awesome amount of practice goes in to be able to play a piece of Beethoven or something or even to move

77
00:08:26,769 --> 00:08:30,636
with that amazing alacrity of a tennis player.

78
00:08:30,696 --> 00:08:32,639
I mean, the ball's moving at 100 miles an hour.

79
00:08:33,139 --> 00:08:36,344
They're not thinking about, well, should I go over there?

80
00:08:36,965 --> 00:08:38,206
Or should I hit it back strong?

81
00:08:38,226 --> 00:08:39,168
Should I spin round?

82
00:08:39,208 --> 00:08:40,429
What should I do?

83
00:08:40,450 --> 00:08:40,811
It's gone.

84
00:08:43,134 --> 00:08:50,605
And this, of course, takes you into things like Zen, which is really high on that sort of spontaneity.

85
00:08:51,427 --> 00:08:56,254
And it's interesting that what one of the masters of Zen, Takuan, I think his name was called,

86
00:08:57,583 --> 00:09:19,440
uh he talked about stopping but not stopping in my sense what he meant was the mind sticking you see so as soon as the mind sticks on something it sort of loses that spontaneity that's sticking you see so if a sportsman uh just stops even for that moment of doubt of wondering you know what to do that's it they've lost it there's only a moment

87
00:09:19,419 --> 00:09:29,958
If a performer just for one moment loses confidence or feels they've lost some concentration, that's it, the music is lost.

88
00:09:29,979 --> 00:09:33,424
They hit the wrong note and everybody boos.

89
00:09:34,447 --> 00:09:35,168
Get out of it.

90
00:09:36,193 --> 00:09:49,808
So, spontaneity also demands that sort of concentration and that giving to the moment, but also that sense of complete looseness, where the mind doesn't hold onto something.

91
00:09:50,589 --> 00:09:52,311
Well, this takes practice.

92
00:09:52,772 --> 00:10:03,383
So, if we're looking at virtues, our virtuous life, then it's a case of recognizing that every time there's an opportunity to practice a virtue,

93
00:10:03,363 --> 00:10:20,701
then that also is leading us towards this beautiful spontaneity, you know, where there's a clarity, where there's a wisdom that comes, so that the action is a response through wisdom, not through some murky impulse.

94
00:10:20,721 --> 00:10:26,086
And with it, with wisdom of course, there's a natural happiness comes, a natural feeling of fulfillment.

95
00:10:27,908 --> 00:10:31,412
I'm thinking of one incident there in the scriptures where

96
00:10:32,152 --> 00:10:45,015
There's a monk who's ill, but ill in that sort of very difficult way, you know, smelly, the bowels are loose, and he's probably quite nasty, and the monks don't take care of him.

97
00:10:45,296 --> 00:10:55,053
And when the Buddha hears that this poor man is sort of squirming around in his own juice, he goes with Ananda to look after him, you see.

98
00:10:55,033 --> 00:10:58,198
And there's no doubt in the Buddha's mind as to what has to be done.

99
00:10:58,798 --> 00:11:03,306
And then he turns to the monks and he says, who's going to look after you?

100
00:11:03,326 --> 00:11:07,110
You've no mother, you've no father, you've nobody to help.

101
00:11:07,130 --> 00:11:09,214
If you don't look after yourselves, who's going to look after you?

102
00:11:09,234 --> 00:11:15,023
So he's sort of saying to them that there's a very good reason for tending the sick.

103
00:11:16,303 --> 00:11:19,589
But in his mind, there was no confusion.

104
00:11:20,129 --> 00:11:21,631
Somebody's sick, so you're going to help.

105
00:11:22,303 --> 00:11:24,706
And I think that's one of the meanings of compassion.

106
00:11:25,187 --> 00:11:30,916
In something like compassion we often get confused with grief.

107
00:11:33,399 --> 00:11:38,606
Not only is there a feeling of obligation.

108
00:11:39,087 --> 00:11:43,653
Take for instance somebody who has a poorly parent.

109
00:11:44,376 --> 00:11:54,051
Now, you've got a situation there where somebody's life might be having to change to look after this poorly parent.

110
00:11:54,071 --> 00:12:08,610
And there's a natural feeling of not wanting to do it, a feeling that, you know, why don't they die quickly and get on with it while they destroy my life and all this sort of stuff.

111
00:12:08,630 --> 00:12:13,177
And there's a feeling of compulsiveness, of having to do it, you see.

112
00:12:13,878 --> 00:12:14,298
Now,

113
00:12:15,123 --> 00:12:18,870
That means that we're feeling a duty being imposed upon us.

114
00:12:19,051 --> 00:12:24,062
Now, whenever a duty is imposed upon us, we're always trying to shrug it off.

115
00:12:24,101 --> 00:12:30,475
We always feel it's unfair, it's unjust, and, you know, why me, you know, and all that sort of stuff.

116
00:12:30,495 --> 00:12:33,182
And that sort of...

117
00:12:34,850 --> 00:12:47,726
idea that the beauties that we have towards other people are an imposition by them upon us turns that compassionate act into something which is quite horrible for the person.

118
00:12:48,408 --> 00:12:49,629
They're chewed up inside.

119
00:12:49,649 --> 00:12:50,931
They don't want to do it really.

120
00:12:51,511 --> 00:12:58,980
And it comes out in little angers and not really taking care and moving them towards the window hoping they might jump.

121
00:12:59,361 --> 00:13:01,784
Things like that.

122
00:13:01,764 --> 00:13:02,485
Murder.

123
00:13:03,128 --> 00:13:05,211
All sorts of, I'm fed up.

124
00:13:06,333 --> 00:13:07,216
All I want is the money.

125
00:13:09,779 --> 00:13:18,356
But as soon as you take on the duty as a personal responsibility, the whole thing changes completely.

126
00:13:18,826 --> 00:13:26,879
As soon as you take it on as a personal responsibility, it becomes a source of training, it becomes a source of generosity, a source of compassion.

127
00:13:27,880 --> 00:13:38,798
And it's not anymore a source of personal happiness, a feeling that one's life is being destroyed, because if you take it on as your personal duty, you see it as your personal training.

128
00:13:41,562 --> 00:13:43,787
You're using it for your spiritual benefit.

129
00:13:46,889 --> 00:13:55,076
And in that care, I'm thinking of somebody specific, really, who has to look after his mother, and himself is quite sick.

130
00:13:55,837 --> 00:13:57,379
And it's amazing.

131
00:13:57,438 --> 00:14:00,422
I've known him for years.

132
00:14:00,722 --> 00:14:03,205
I've never heard him complain.

133
00:14:03,225 --> 00:14:05,607
And he's been looking after his mother for years now.

134
00:14:06,427 --> 00:14:11,974
And he seems to just have that very natural generosity.

135
00:14:13,075 --> 00:14:16,238
You know, just, well, this is my mother, and I'll look after her, you know.

136
00:14:16,522 --> 00:14:26,177
And there's no, I don't think, never heard him being bitter or backbiting or talking about the, you know, pain and all that.

137
00:14:26,197 --> 00:14:30,823
And he seems to be in himself quite happy with the whole situation.

138
00:14:31,565 --> 00:14:38,495
And that can only come about because he's taken on that task, that duty as something very personal to him.

139
00:14:39,184 --> 00:15:00,687
So, in all these virtues, if we see them as a path of training, then we understand that the negativity will arise, but just like, I mean, this is what the Vipassana is for, it makes us sort of more globally aware of what's happening within us.

140
00:15:00,667 --> 00:15:09,655
So when we practice a virtue and we can see the negativity come up, then we're not hijacked by it, we actually see it.

141
00:15:09,755 --> 00:15:25,711
Even if it's there, and even if it's putting a certain nasty feeling into the equation, the point is, we can distance from it, know it's there, and not act according to those suggestions, to those negative suggestions.

142
00:15:25,692 --> 00:15:29,356
And then we put the positive suggestion in our mind and we act from that.

143
00:15:29,837 --> 00:15:32,541
And at first it feels difficult, at first it feels hard.

144
00:15:34,102 --> 00:15:37,727
But eventually, as it were, the heart's being reconditioned.

145
00:15:38,850 --> 00:15:48,121
Now, here, when we were talking yesterday about the will, you can see that the will is something separate from emotions, is something separate from thoughts.

146
00:15:48,524 --> 00:15:54,431
The will is something which empowers, and the practice is leading us to a point of wisdom.

147
00:15:55,111 --> 00:16:15,375
So every time a situation comes up which we are uncomfortable with, that we don't want, that we're fighting against, struggling against, so you have to be quite clear to yourself that that's the negativity coming from some sort of delusive thought, from some sort of misunderstanding.

148
00:16:15,355 --> 00:16:25,530
And it's allowing that misunderstanding and allowing the emotions that that misunderstanding is producing to come up into consciousness and for them to be recognized.

149
00:16:26,412 --> 00:16:28,134
As soon as you did that, you're doing vipassana.

150
00:16:28,855 --> 00:16:29,857
You've separated out.

151
00:16:29,918 --> 00:16:34,544
You see it as some negative conditioning within us.

152
00:16:35,960 --> 00:16:40,547
And then sometimes one has to wait for that to dissolve a little bit.

153
00:16:41,567 --> 00:16:49,299
But even so, even if it's there in a very strong way, you can always bring the right intention to mind and you do it with right intention.

154
00:16:49,840 --> 00:16:52,683
Even though within yourself you might feel horrible.

155
00:16:53,304 --> 00:16:53,865
This is the point.

156
00:16:54,606 --> 00:16:58,052
In yourself you might feel down, you might feel depressed, etc., etc.

157
00:16:58,493 --> 00:17:02,658
But there's this intention which you empower and you keep working that way.

158
00:17:03,297 --> 00:17:12,828
Now, with the action, with the good intention and with the action, it's bound to begin to develop the right attitude.

159
00:17:13,769 --> 00:17:18,496
The right attitude has always been there, it's just begun to develop.

160
00:17:19,176 --> 00:17:26,065
And when you have right attitude, in time, it has a systemic effect, so the heart begins to respond.

161
00:17:27,344 --> 00:17:35,433
And all those negative feelings that we have begin to dissolve and this more positive feeling begins to arise.

162
00:17:37,717 --> 00:17:40,099
I mean, I'll just give you a personal example.

163
00:17:41,801 --> 00:17:48,109
I've never, until maybe five or six years ago, ever wanted to teach.

164
00:17:48,170 --> 00:17:49,892
I don't know what I'm doing here.

165
00:17:51,964 --> 00:17:53,006
It was the most...

166
00:17:53,026 --> 00:17:59,875
I remember when I was sitting on a beach in Alicante, down in Spain somewhere, with a bottle of Zangria.

167
00:18:00,796 --> 00:18:07,664
And I went down to the post office to get this telegram from my father, who said, you know, you've got your BA and your teacher's certificate, and he said, congratulations.

168
00:18:07,684 --> 00:18:11,229
And I went and sat on this rock overlooking the sea, the Mediterranean, isn't it?

169
00:18:11,970 --> 00:18:15,795
And I remember distinctly saying, there is no way I want to teach.

170
00:18:16,061 --> 00:18:16,663
That was it.

171
00:18:17,065 --> 00:18:19,109
And I didn't for about two or three years.

172
00:18:19,210 --> 00:18:21,675
But then, of course, you know, you need money.

173
00:18:24,202 --> 00:18:32,063
And when I came back to Britain, and I realized that I didn't want to go back east again, and that I wanted to stay here,

174
00:18:32,109 --> 00:18:50,195
I also realized that there's no way I can exist in a country which doesn't have an infrastructure to support the monastic life, unless you've got ethnic groups supporting you, like the Thais or the Burmese or something, which I didn't have.

175
00:18:50,817 --> 00:18:55,864
There's no way you can exist as a monastic unless you give something to lay people.

176
00:18:57,066 --> 00:18:57,846
They won't give you money.

177
00:18:59,569 --> 00:19:01,172
Westerners don't give you money for nothing.

178
00:19:01,574 --> 00:19:05,402
So I realized that I had to teach.

179
00:19:05,481 --> 00:19:08,509
I felt it was a bit of a...

180
00:19:09,130 --> 00:19:11,094
It was a necessary contract.

181
00:19:11,875 --> 00:19:17,827
And I took on what's known as the Dhammadutta, which is the...

182
00:19:18,854 --> 00:19:21,478
the duty of teaching the Dharma.

183
00:19:21,498 --> 00:19:30,792
So in this country, you'll hear certain monks, or you'll hear in the conversation, especially amongst Sri Lankans, that they're a Dharmadutta monk, which means that they're missionaries.

184
00:19:31,374 --> 00:19:32,596
That's what it is, you know, mission.

185
00:19:33,917 --> 00:19:36,221
Come to a foreign land to convert the heathen.

186
00:19:38,075 --> 00:19:40,118
So I made that decision.

187
00:19:40,159 --> 00:19:54,784
But even so, there was a long, long time I just felt this negativity, which I only shared with close students, that this was something that was really against the grain because I didn't want to do it.

188
00:19:57,160 --> 00:20:03,410
And then, of course, that negativity sort of builds up, and you think, well, what's happening here?

189
00:20:03,851 --> 00:20:05,012
I've got to look at this.

190
00:20:05,554 --> 00:20:09,840
And so this was 98, between 98 and 99.

191
00:20:10,402 --> 00:20:14,107
And I went to Upandita's center.

192
00:20:14,127 --> 00:20:17,653
It's named after him, of course, Upandita Rama.

193
00:20:17,673 --> 00:20:23,083
And when I was there, I came across, I'm sure you've all heard of that book, A Course in Miracles.

194
00:20:23,738 --> 00:20:26,122
And I came across a little book.

195
00:20:26,884 --> 00:20:29,669
It's really strange because I was struggling with this business of teaching.

196
00:20:31,352 --> 00:20:42,913
I mean, the alternative was to basically return to the East and return to my little hut, which tended to gain a certain glow after my hut.

197
00:20:43,012 --> 00:20:44,936
What happened to my hut?

198
00:20:45,742 --> 00:20:50,691
And I came across this little book, which is one of these serendipity things, which you can't really explain.

199
00:20:51,030 --> 00:20:53,074
And here I am wondering about what to do.

200
00:20:53,094 --> 00:21:02,048
And this little book was a collection out of the Course in Miracles on teaching and the purpose of teaching and that sort of stuff.

201
00:21:02,067 --> 00:21:07,036
Now, I can't remember it, but by the end of that book, I was convinced that this was actually a good path to be on.

202
00:21:07,717 --> 00:21:09,759
So I have the Course in Miracles to thank.

203
00:21:11,191 --> 00:21:16,411
And then once that attitude changed, the negativity didn't go.

204
00:21:16,772 --> 00:21:18,137
See, the negativity is still there.

205
00:21:19,423 --> 00:21:21,791
And even now, occasionally, I'll get this, you know, God.

206
00:21:22,767 --> 00:21:25,211
I don't want to go in there and give a talk.

207
00:21:25,892 --> 00:21:27,073
I want to sit in there and go, tea.

208
00:21:28,115 --> 00:21:29,155
See?

209
00:21:29,557 --> 00:21:36,606
But it's no longer that awful mental state that was coming up for about a year when I just felt I was wasting time.

210
00:21:36,626 --> 00:21:37,929
I mean, that's what comes, you see.

211
00:21:38,650 --> 00:21:42,035
My inclination is to be a recluse.

212
00:21:42,516 --> 00:21:43,676
So I'm wasting time.

213
00:21:43,857 --> 00:21:45,038
I mean, that's the big thing, you see.

214
00:21:45,058 --> 00:21:48,183
I should be in there, you know, knocking my head against the wall.

215
00:21:48,163 --> 00:21:49,566
I shouldn't be out here teaching.

216
00:21:49,905 --> 00:22:00,701
So that sort of negativity, even though it comes up occasionally, it actually is just a dying conditioning, you might say.

217
00:22:01,422 --> 00:22:13,597
And that the more I gave myself to the teaching, especially when I went to Gaia House, the more I gave to it, the more, to my surprise, there came this lovely feeling of joy.

218
00:22:14,017 --> 00:22:18,925
I didn't say to myself, right, I've got to feel joy when I go in there.

219
00:22:19,207 --> 00:22:19,547
I didn't.

220
00:22:19,928 --> 00:22:30,769
And the more I began to give talks, the more they became sort of spontaneous in the sense that even now I've not prepared it.

221
00:22:31,349 --> 00:22:33,394
You just come in and you speak and hope for the best.

222
00:22:33,994 --> 00:22:34,455
And that's it.

223
00:22:34,635 --> 00:22:36,700
Just make sure I haven't got any bricks.

224
00:22:38,266 --> 00:22:42,018
So it was that sort of passage.

225
00:22:42,057 --> 00:22:46,352
Now, I think if you look in your own lives, I'm sure you'll find something which

226
00:22:47,142 --> 00:23:03,798
gets you down or whatever and it's a case of looking at that and accepting the motivation there, looking at that motivation and seeing what is it you're doing to make a job which previously you might have been happy with suddenly miserable.

227
00:23:04,220 --> 00:23:11,007
What is it you're doing to make something which you can see quite clearly could be very beautiful.

228
00:23:11,240 --> 00:23:17,105
could be a real growth area for you, something that you see as a sort of hell realm.

229
00:23:18,768 --> 00:23:20,269
A lot of people do that with their jobs.

230
00:23:20,970 --> 00:23:27,916
At first they walk in and they're sort of pretty excited by it, most times.

231
00:23:28,978 --> 00:23:31,861
And they're looking forward to it and then they get into it and they like it.

232
00:23:32,501 --> 00:23:35,984
A few months down the line, a couple of years down the line, it's, I've got to get out of here.

233
00:23:37,686 --> 00:23:40,690
It takes on a board and it takes on all those sorts of things.

234
00:23:42,256 --> 00:23:50,182
And it's interesting because even in the most menial tasks, even in the most menial tasks, there's spiritual training.

235
00:23:52,028 --> 00:23:55,319
Even in something so repetitive of being on a production line,

236
00:23:55,434 --> 00:24:04,165
can be a process whereby you grow in concentration just by putting your mind on exactly the same action.

237
00:24:04,567 --> 00:24:05,688
I mean, what are we doing here?

238
00:24:06,009 --> 00:24:07,130
We do walking meditation.

239
00:24:07,310 --> 00:24:08,291
It's exactly the same thing.

240
00:24:08,992 --> 00:24:13,097
We're lifting, moving, lowering, placing, up and down, up and down.

241
00:24:13,439 --> 00:24:16,923
We do it for 40 minutes, an hour, four or five times a day.

242
00:24:17,364 --> 00:24:19,906
By the end of the week, you've walked hours going up and down.

243
00:24:20,327 --> 00:24:22,911
But you've never thought to yourself, well, this is really boring.

244
00:24:22,971 --> 00:24:24,413
I should be paid more for this.

245
00:24:24,393 --> 00:24:26,141
This is ridiculous.

246
00:24:26,382 --> 00:24:27,307
I'm being abused.

247
00:24:27,326 --> 00:24:32,309
I have to write a nasty letter to Bodhidharma.

248
00:24:34,855 --> 00:24:46,390
So it's even in something sort of so repetitive or so menial, which we all do at some point just in our household chores, you know, just cleaning the toilet.

249
00:24:46,410 --> 00:24:49,653
I mean, that's considered a menial task, you know.

250
00:24:49,673 --> 00:25:03,731
But to actually bring a joy to it, to actually see it as purposeful, to actually see that it's something that you can develop a certain care, you know, cleaning the toilet bowl, we can do it with care and attention.

251
00:25:04,825 --> 00:25:06,067
You know what I mean?

252
00:25:06,086 --> 00:25:25,815
And it's these, like you walk into these public toilets, you see, and there's either a man or a woman sitting there, and sometimes I go and I think, I wonder what sort of life it is down here in the Jakes, you know, living in this subterranean world with the smell of urine.

253
00:25:25,875 --> 00:25:29,701
And I think, God, you know, this must be a hell realm, you know.

254
00:25:29,721 --> 00:25:31,403
And some of them do give you that impression.

255
00:25:31,644 --> 00:25:34,748
I mean, they really are, you know, they don't want to know, you know.

256
00:25:35,875 --> 00:25:38,179
But the other day I was in, where was I?

257
00:25:38,660 --> 00:25:39,761
Some station or other.

258
00:25:40,623 --> 00:25:42,045
I was in some station.

259
00:25:42,065 --> 00:25:44,409
And there was a woman at the main kiosk.

260
00:25:44,429 --> 00:25:46,172
And she was having the time of her life.

261
00:25:47,253 --> 00:25:54,346
She was having a chat with people and drawing their attention and shouting out about toilet paper and all sorts of stuff.

262
00:25:54,365 --> 00:25:55,667
And she was okay.

263
00:25:55,989 --> 00:25:57,211
You could feel she was okay.

264
00:25:57,230 --> 00:25:58,834
And everybody was okay with it, you know.

265
00:25:59,394 --> 00:26:02,118
It was a completely different sort of toilet I've ever been in.

266
00:26:04,141 --> 00:26:15,336
So it's like as soon as you see every situation you're in as something to train in, then that sort of joy arises.

267
00:26:15,376 --> 00:26:17,641
And with the joy comes the spontaneity.

268
00:26:19,903 --> 00:26:21,747
So you've got these two lines.

269
00:26:21,807 --> 00:26:30,839
You've got both the trying to undermine old attitudes, bringing up a good reason for doing things,

270
00:26:31,157 --> 00:26:35,085
And by doing that, the heart responds.

271
00:26:35,205 --> 00:26:36,248
It's just as simple as that.

272
00:26:37,509 --> 00:26:51,916
And we may surprise ourselves occasionally by doing something quite spontaneously, which on reflection we realize has actually come from pure wisdom, that we've actually done it out of that really good heart, one way or the other.

273
00:27:03,557 --> 00:27:08,605
So if we just look at one or two of these, well, I've not got much time now.

274
00:27:09,226 --> 00:27:12,371
One or two of these, that trilogy is interesting.

275
00:27:17,298 --> 00:27:30,357
Well, take, I mean, the ten perfections are, we haven't got time to go through them all, is giving and morality, which morality is good conduct, slightly better.

276
00:27:30,625 --> 00:27:38,928
renunciation, wisdom itself, energy, patience, truthfulness, resolution, loving-kindness, and equanimity.

277
00:27:40,472 --> 00:27:42,458
But just to take patience, for instance,

278
00:27:44,210 --> 00:28:11,250
patience, that patient forbearance, that feels like an imposition, you know, like with a naughty child or with somebody who's messing you about, or that great nuisance, you know, the thumping bass beat through the wall while he's trying to sit there, trying to do some reading or meditating, you know, murderous thoughts arise.

279
00:28:12,232 --> 00:28:12,933
And

280
00:28:13,875 --> 00:28:21,844
that patience, that ability to bear with the uncomfortable, to bear with that which one does not want.

281
00:28:22,651 --> 00:28:29,280
Now, normally speaking, when something arises that we don't want, you get that negativity, you get the aversion, you get the anger.

282
00:28:30,963 --> 00:28:34,828
But to be able to allow that to come, it's always the same process.

283
00:28:34,910 --> 00:28:37,472
You allow that negativity to arise.

284
00:28:37,854 --> 00:28:43,442
If you push it away, if you bat it away, then it just remains there as a conditioning.

285
00:28:44,223 --> 00:28:49,131
And the power of your suppression is in a sense like pushing a spring down.

286
00:28:49,313 --> 00:28:51,255
And that's how these rages happen, you see.

287
00:28:51,695 --> 00:28:54,259
People don't realize how much anger they've built up in themselves.

288
00:28:54,338 --> 00:28:56,361
And then suddenly they do something which is quite awful.

289
00:29:01,426 --> 00:29:03,888
So one actually feels that negativity, you see.

290
00:29:04,150 --> 00:29:05,411
And then you have to recognize it.

291
00:29:05,431 --> 00:29:07,933
You have to label it as unwholesome.

292
00:29:08,755 --> 00:29:12,019
And then, as it were, you change your attitude.

293
00:29:12,679 --> 00:29:16,923
And the great phrase for patience is, this is the way it is.

294
00:29:18,912 --> 00:29:23,719
As soon as you say, this is the way it should not be, you're into conflict.

295
00:29:24,159 --> 00:29:25,181
You know, this is how it...

296
00:29:25,201 --> 00:29:25,922
It shouldn't be like this.

297
00:29:27,544 --> 00:29:29,666
Did you ever see that film, Unforgiven?

298
00:29:29,946 --> 00:29:30,587
Clint Eastwood.

299
00:29:31,009 --> 00:29:34,554
Classic sort of silly western.

300
00:29:35,174 --> 00:29:37,577
And at the end, of course, he shoots everybody.

301
00:29:39,099 --> 00:29:39,800
And everybody's dead.

302
00:29:40,122 --> 00:29:40,642
And there's...

303
00:29:40,662 --> 00:29:41,844
I can't remember the name of the actor.

304
00:29:41,864 --> 00:29:42,744
He's very, very good.

305
00:29:43,246 --> 00:29:46,911
But his dying words are, this shouldn't have happened.

306
00:29:49,522 --> 00:29:50,346
This shouldn't have happened.

307
00:29:52,212 --> 00:29:54,280
I mean, that's it, isn't it?

308
00:29:54,361 --> 00:29:55,284
That's where we are.

309
00:29:55,325 --> 00:29:56,528
It shouldn't be like this.

310
00:29:56,829 --> 00:29:57,692
It should be other.

311
00:29:58,095 --> 00:29:59,780
Why am I suffering this?

312
00:30:00,001 --> 00:30:01,086
All that sort of stuff.

313
00:30:01,740 --> 00:30:17,297
But as soon as you start using the phrase, start grounding yourself in the present moment as it really is, this is the way it is, then the patience comes as a sort of acceptance, an acceptance of this is the way it is.

314
00:30:17,317 --> 00:30:20,059
Now, when we do that, we sometimes get confused.

315
00:30:20,079 --> 00:30:22,162
We think, oh, well, that's some form of resignation.

316
00:30:22,663 --> 00:30:31,511
But the distinction between these two is that when somebody resigns themselves to something in that sort of bad sense, they disempower themselves.

317
00:30:31,491 --> 00:30:39,483
You know, this is it, I can't do anything, you know, I'm miserable, and that's the way life is, it's horrible, and whinge, and all that sort of stuff.

318
00:30:39,503 --> 00:30:50,579
And that, of course, is really harmful spiritually, because at that point, you're conquered, you're destroyed by what it is you've resigned to.

319
00:30:50,981 --> 00:30:53,945
But acceptance is a completely different attitude.

320
00:30:54,006 --> 00:31:07,964
Acceptance is that beginning with the ground of, this is the way it is, and then with that sort of patience, with that ability to accept the way it is, then there arises what can be done.

321
00:31:09,066 --> 00:31:09,205
See?

322
00:31:09,606 --> 00:31:12,250
When one sees a situation, there's always something can be done.

323
00:31:12,349 --> 00:31:14,252
I mean, if it's music, you can always go for a walk.

324
00:31:15,414 --> 00:31:16,276
Or buy a gun or something.

325
00:31:17,176 --> 00:31:17,277
Yeah.

326
00:31:19,061 --> 00:31:23,409
There's always something can be done to alleviate it.

327
00:31:23,449 --> 00:31:24,670
You know, earplugs.

328
00:31:24,971 --> 00:31:26,553
That's an alleviation.

329
00:31:27,974 --> 00:31:28,977
There was a lovely...

330
00:31:29,738 --> 00:31:30,759
I used to know this fellow.

331
00:31:31,140 --> 00:31:32,021
I wonder how he is now.

332
00:31:32,201 --> 00:31:33,723
I often wonder about him.

333
00:31:33,743 --> 00:31:34,424
He was a big man.

334
00:31:35,426 --> 00:31:36,488
Strong, you know, toughy.

335
00:31:36,528 --> 00:31:38,751
I mean, when you saw him, you didn't want to say the wrong word.

336
00:31:39,573 --> 00:31:40,974
And he was the head of the Communist Party.

337
00:31:41,615 --> 00:31:42,657
This was before it disbanded.

338
00:31:43,219 --> 00:31:44,119
This is going back a while.

339
00:31:44,180 --> 00:31:46,182
And...

340
00:31:46,332 --> 00:31:52,122
He was with his partner, and they had a room right at the top of the house, or the flat at the top of the house.

341
00:31:52,864 --> 00:32:03,362
And these students came in, or I'm not sure who the students, young kids came in next door, and started playing rock music, the practicing, you know, drums and everything, 12 o'clock at night.

342
00:32:04,642 --> 00:32:11,593
Okay, so he goes down, knocks on the door, and they come, and he says, you know, knock, you know, noise, this time of night.

343
00:32:11,613 --> 00:32:13,255
They say, yeah, all right, all right.

344
00:32:13,275 --> 00:32:15,878
And they stop, you see.

345
00:32:16,420 --> 00:32:20,527
Either next night or a couple of nights on.

346
00:32:20,807 --> 00:32:23,010
So down he goes again, knocks on the door.

347
00:32:23,030 --> 00:32:26,736
The guy comes out and says, you know, you know, a bit more angry, you know.

348
00:32:27,538 --> 00:32:29,240
And they say, okay, okay, we'll stop, we'll stop.

349
00:32:29,259 --> 00:32:30,362
So they stop.

350
00:32:30,342 --> 00:32:35,490
So the third time, there's music, he goes down, goes out the door, and he just went, whop, right on his nose.

351
00:32:36,250 --> 00:32:37,311
That was it, end of music.

352
00:32:40,797 --> 00:32:44,823
Sometimes a hard lesson is needed.

353
00:32:45,384 --> 00:32:50,832
And I used to just laugh when I heard of that, you know.

354
00:32:52,027 --> 00:32:53,209
He was a lovely man, you see.

355
00:32:53,348 --> 00:32:54,130
He was very patient.

356
00:32:54,211 --> 00:32:55,112
You know, he'd been woken up.

357
00:32:55,132 --> 00:32:56,334
He has to get his clothes on.

358
00:32:56,354 --> 00:32:57,817
He has to go down, knock on the door.

359
00:32:57,856 --> 00:32:58,837
Can you please stop?

360
00:32:58,857 --> 00:33:00,401
He goes down a second time, third time.

361
00:33:00,441 --> 00:33:00,741
Enough.

362
00:33:01,482 --> 00:33:01,782
Clunk.

363
00:33:01,823 --> 00:33:02,565
And that's the end of that.

364
00:33:02,585 --> 00:33:03,726
And they don't play music again.

365
00:33:03,746 --> 00:33:08,654
It's like... Now, I'm not suggesting.

366
00:33:11,720 --> 00:33:15,486
But it's that ability to...

367
00:33:16,039 --> 00:33:28,242
accept the way things are, wherever we are, especially, of course, those times when we feel uncomfortable or in a situation which we find hard to bear.

368
00:33:28,492 --> 00:33:30,994
just accepting it.

369
00:33:31,055 --> 00:33:34,439
It's like you're accepting the load.

370
00:33:34,459 --> 00:33:38,301
Instead of trying to shrug it off, it's like carrying a haversack or a rucksack.

371
00:33:38,321 --> 00:33:41,484
If you're carrying a rucksack and you don't want it in your back, it really is painful.

372
00:33:42,766 --> 00:33:49,271
But if you accept that you need this rucksack in order to wander over the world, then you're quite happy having this huge weight on your back.

373
00:33:49,772 --> 00:33:50,814
You don't complain about it.

374
00:33:51,054 --> 00:33:54,277
You carry your house, your washing machine, they're all on the back.

375
00:33:55,077 --> 00:33:57,640
And you're quite happy carrying this huge weight.

376
00:33:57,619 --> 00:33:58,782
It's amazing when you think about it.

377
00:33:59,243 --> 00:34:01,088
And campers, you see, they want to go camping.

378
00:34:01,108 --> 00:34:06,845
They don't mind carrying these huge weights on their back in order to go out and camp in the wilderness.

379
00:34:07,646 --> 00:34:10,454
But as soon as somebody says to you, would you carry this for me?

380
00:34:10,474 --> 00:34:11,096
You say, oh, yeah.

381
00:34:11,115 --> 00:34:11,577
And they go, ooh.

382
00:34:12,440 --> 00:34:13,181
So what?

383
00:34:13,161 --> 00:34:42,594
so it's that lovely way that we can train ourselves this is the point about our spiritual life we can actually train ourselves to be like this so this is the way it is and the anger goes as soon as you accept the situation as it is and then always at least to my amazement there's always a way of dealing with the situation there's always a way of alleviating the situation in some way or other

384
00:34:44,751 --> 00:34:51,280
And it's just through that practice of patience that, in a sense, it just becomes part and parcel.

385
00:34:51,742 --> 00:34:59,413
Now, I've been here now for three years, and I haven't run a centre before.

386
00:34:59,753 --> 00:35:02,376
I mean, you know, this is a new experience for me, running a centre.

387
00:35:03,719 --> 00:35:04,780
And thank goodness it's small.

388
00:35:05,742 --> 00:35:09,987
And people do things which, you know, get up my nose.

389
00:35:10,809 --> 00:35:14,134
If people come here and they do things, I think, what the hell are they...

390
00:35:15,802 --> 00:35:17,965
They go, I just want to pick the flowers.

391
00:35:20,010 --> 00:35:20,590
Pick the flowers.

392
00:35:20,751 --> 00:35:21,251
Put them up there.

393
00:35:21,271 --> 00:35:21,893
It's very nice.

394
00:35:22,835 --> 00:35:26,561
But like, you know, it's always, you know.

395
00:35:26,581 --> 00:35:28,885
And you get people, you know, putting carpets.

396
00:35:28,905 --> 00:35:31,771
You know, you have a carpet, they come back and it's put over here.

397
00:35:32,452 --> 00:35:34,315
You know, like, why?

398
00:35:34,416 --> 00:35:35,197
Why are they doing that?

399
00:35:35,858 --> 00:35:38,382
You know, they've come to change me.

400
00:35:38,853 --> 00:35:43,920
So, and it's been, you know, and having to work with managers, you can't use it.

401
00:35:46,605 --> 00:35:56,101
And you just get, and after a while, you see these irritations, you know, you see these irritations, and you keep saying to yourself, what am I getting, you know, why am I getting irritated?

402
00:35:56,221 --> 00:35:57,943
You know, this is really silly.

403
00:35:58,083 --> 00:36:04,273
I mean, to actually have, you know, these little Bernie things going on in me, for what?

404
00:36:04,313 --> 00:36:06,177
And actually silly things anyway.

405
00:36:06,730 --> 00:36:21,786
And slowly, because you see, one of the dangers of living as a recluse or living by yourself in a hut or living by yourself in society, living in your own flat, you know, is that you forget how to live with people.

406
00:36:21,918 --> 00:36:30,773
You know, it's like, I mean, I was brought up with brothers and sisters, so we always shared a bedroom, you know.

407
00:36:31,333 --> 00:36:33,436
These days kids have a room of their own.

408
00:36:34,237 --> 00:36:40,027
Sharing is like a pain, you know, like it becomes a war.

409
00:36:40,818 --> 00:36:51,532
And just to be able to allow these irritations to actually see them for what they are, just silly places where the mind grabs, places where the mind is upadana, is grasping, you see.

410
00:36:52,132 --> 00:36:56,880
And then, you know, you just sort of recognize this is not doing you any good, it's just absolutely silly.

411
00:36:57,420 --> 00:36:59,583
And you begin to relax, you begin to relax.

412
00:36:59,603 --> 00:37:06,032
And you never approach the person in that state of anger, because if you approach that state of anger, for sure,

413
00:37:06,012 --> 00:37:08,597
you express it in some way, you know.

414
00:37:09,077 --> 00:37:14,907
It might be just the trembling of your hands as you're talking, you know, but something will sort of leak out.

415
00:37:15,750 --> 00:37:20,458
And in that way, unwittingly, you're sort of engineering this anger.

416
00:37:20,818 --> 00:37:23,543
So you have to sit with it, you know, wait, wait, wait.

417
00:37:24,164 --> 00:37:25,927
And at...

418
00:37:25,907 --> 00:37:31,576
And I found, for instance, at the beginning, it would take three days for these little angers to disappear.

419
00:37:32,077 --> 00:37:33,018
It would take them for three days.

420
00:37:33,077 --> 00:37:35,822
I'd be sat here thinking, this is ridiculous, you know.

421
00:37:36,282 --> 00:37:53,788
And very slowly, just by accepting this is the way it is, it's quite surprising how quickly those old habits begin to be disempowered and just a more natural ability just to be with the way it is, to be with people as they are, you know.

422
00:37:54,376 --> 00:37:57,409
I mean, I'm very lucky here because most people come here with good intent.

423
00:37:57,992 --> 00:37:58,434
You know what I mean?

424
00:37:58,454 --> 00:38:01,065
It's not as though they ripped the flowers up to ruin the garden.

425
00:38:01,728 --> 00:38:03,153
You know, it's like...

426
00:38:04,297 --> 00:38:07,262
I mean, I'm surrounded by people with good intents.

427
00:38:07,302 --> 00:38:08,643
I mean, that makes it much easier.

428
00:38:09,545 --> 00:38:14,632
But at work, you might find yourself with people who have their knives out for you.

429
00:38:14,672 --> 00:38:18,416
I'm thinking of one person who was terribly bullied.

430
00:38:19,557 --> 00:38:24,565
And in those sorts of situations, yes, you accept the way things are.

431
00:38:24,784 --> 00:38:28,630
This is the way it is, but you definitely don't allow that to go on.

432
00:38:28,771 --> 00:38:32,735
You find ways of undermining that sort of really bad behavior.

433
00:38:34,387 --> 00:38:54,074
But if you don't accept the situation as it is, then either you're deluding yourself, such as, you know, this person really isn't bullying me, you know, and this is the way it ought to be, or you're just getting yourself into huge fits of anger, frustration, and a final sort of giving in to the situation, of a sort of resignation, you know.

434
00:38:54,693 --> 00:38:56,836
And that's really bad spiritually.

435
00:38:56,856 --> 00:38:57,838
Really bad spiritually.

436
00:38:58,219 --> 00:38:59,601
Both ways are bad spiritually.

437
00:39:00,289 --> 00:39:08,543
So, slowly, you know, by, through this process of seeing where anger arises, see, that's your sign of impatience.

438
00:39:08,643 --> 00:39:10,186
That's the sign there's no patience.

439
00:39:10,206 --> 00:39:16,077
Wherever anger or irritation arises, you can say, this is the lack of patience, right?

440
00:39:16,657 --> 00:39:18,822
And you're holding on to something, right?

441
00:39:18,802 --> 00:39:24,076
If you have children and they do something which makes you angry, then you're holding on to something.

442
00:39:24,097 --> 00:39:25,320
There's no need for the anger.

443
00:39:26,322 --> 00:39:28,748
Even with children, there's no actual need for the anger.

444
00:39:29,351 --> 00:39:34,143
You might manifest anger to get your own way.

445
00:39:34,123 --> 00:39:38,070
But to actually feel it in your heart is not actually necessary.

446
00:39:38,992 --> 00:39:44,300
That's something we are putting into the situation by saying, this is not the way it should be.

447
00:39:45,181 --> 00:39:45,963
This should be other.

448
00:39:46,543 --> 00:39:50,710
I'm not accepting the situation completely as it is.

449
00:39:51,711 --> 00:39:54,697
And with that patience, there always comes a natural wisdom.

450
00:39:55,918 --> 00:39:57,101
It arises naturally.

451
00:39:57,380 --> 00:39:58,983
You don't have to work at it.

452
00:39:59,351 --> 00:40:13,106
And I think the more you find yourself becoming patient, the more this wise response to situations arises spontaneously, arises without having to, you know, work at it so much.

453
00:40:20,452 --> 00:40:25,478
And you can take all the other virtues, giving, you see, giving...

454
00:40:27,652 --> 00:40:34,902
Our moral life, you know, you find yourself, so we say, over-exaggerating in your speech.

455
00:40:36,045 --> 00:40:37,527
It's a form of wrong speech.

456
00:40:37,547 --> 00:40:40,391
It's a form of not speaking the truth.

457
00:40:41,172 --> 00:40:48,023
And just by recognizing that, you accept it, you see, and you come back and you correct yourself.

458
00:40:48,083 --> 00:40:49,947
You're slightly more clear.

459
00:40:50,007 --> 00:40:51,869
You're slightly more careful about what you say.

460
00:40:54,753 --> 00:40:57,981
Renunciation, you see?

461
00:40:58,021 --> 00:41:07,463
Renunciation is, if you're doing it as a sort of self-hate thing, or for any other reason apart from seeing where your attachment is, there's probably some wrong intention there.

462
00:41:07,483 --> 00:41:11,192
The whole point of renunciation is to see the attachment.

463
00:41:11,340 --> 00:41:19,231
So if you decide to have a look at your eating habits and you decide to fast or to do without a meal, you're doing it in order to see the habit.

464
00:41:19,632 --> 00:41:21,094
You're not doing it for any other reason.

465
00:41:21,634 --> 00:41:24,918
If you do it for some other reason, then maybe some aversion come into it.

466
00:41:24,938 --> 00:41:28,342
Maybe some trying to control come into it.

467
00:41:28,963 --> 00:41:34,311
But remember, if you try to control habits, you're into a battle with them.

468
00:41:34,679 --> 00:41:46,777
What we're learning here is to allow the feelings to arise, but then always make sure they're not translated into an action, an action of thought, word or deed.

469
00:41:48,519 --> 00:41:55,769
But if you're in the habit of controlling it, which means you're pushing away, you're trying to hold it, there's always some negativity there.

470
00:41:56,331 --> 00:42:00,197
And that isn't right renunciation.

471
00:42:01,342 --> 00:42:02,284
Energy, you see.

472
00:42:03,184 --> 00:42:04,688
Here we're learning how to be calm.

473
00:42:05,248 --> 00:42:15,527
There's no need to get over-energetic in things, to put your energy in things which sort of pump up the energy.

474
00:42:16,568 --> 00:42:24,802
What we're learning here is that if you do things calmly, the energy necessary for a particular task arises naturally.

475
00:42:25,202 --> 00:42:26,826
You don't have to go over the top with it.

476
00:42:28,088 --> 00:42:29,469
And then there's patience.

477
00:42:29,489 --> 00:42:35,297
We've had truthfulness, which we've talked a little bit about, especially in terms of exaggeration.

478
00:42:36,057 --> 00:42:37,119
Resolution, you see.

479
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:41,623
Every day we have that moment after chanting to make a resolution.

480
00:42:43,266 --> 00:42:47,510
If it's done with a good heart, if it's done with real resolve, you'd be surprised.

481
00:42:47,550 --> 00:42:48,693
It does work its way through.

482
00:42:48,733 --> 00:42:53,217
It does actually come through.

483
00:42:53,282 --> 00:42:53,943
Eventually.

484
00:42:54,043 --> 00:43:03,518
Of course, every time, if you're resolving not to do something because it's negative, every time that negativity comes up, you have to bring that resolution to mind.

485
00:43:04,659 --> 00:43:05,601
Even if you indulge.

486
00:43:05,661 --> 00:43:08,766
So you say to yourself, you know, I will not drink any more coffee.

487
00:43:09,166 --> 00:43:09,487
Right?

488
00:43:09,507 --> 00:43:11,911
And you're walking down the street and Costa Coffee grabs your nose.

489
00:43:12,512 --> 00:43:19,242
See, and you think, ah, and then you hear yourself, I will not drink, and hmm, and then you go, and you're drinking coffee, see?

490
00:43:19,541 --> 00:43:21,585
Then you say to yourself, okay.

491
00:43:21,733 --> 00:43:22,534
I drank coffee.

492
00:43:23,135 --> 00:43:24,878
You see?

493
00:43:24,898 --> 00:43:27,443
And you drink your coffee and you say, then you make a resolution.

494
00:43:27,483 --> 00:43:29,746
Next time, no.

495
00:43:30,106 --> 00:43:30,307
You see?

496
00:43:31,949 --> 00:43:34,554
And eventually, to your surprise, Costa Coffee will come.

497
00:43:35,014 --> 00:43:38,019
Grab your nose, but the body will keep moving past.

498
00:43:38,800 --> 00:43:38,981
You see?

499
00:43:40,043 --> 00:43:41,945
It won't have that huge effect on you.

500
00:43:43,307 --> 00:43:44,690
Loving kindness, you see?

501
00:43:44,751 --> 00:43:45,632
It's...

502
00:43:46,338 --> 00:44:03,385
case of that, I mean, they translate metta as loving kindness, which is all right, it's more the heart side, but it's goodwill, you know, it's that goodwill, and just having that as a basic attitude to all beings, you know, wishing them well.

503
00:44:03,364 --> 00:44:06,789
And in the morning just to practice that after your vipassana.

504
00:44:07,168 --> 00:44:10,673
So remember the vipassana has to be brought into an attitude.

505
00:44:11,173 --> 00:44:13,257
Vipassana is about understanding and wisdom.

506
00:44:13,717 --> 00:44:15,719
You have to translate it into an attitude.

507
00:44:15,820 --> 00:44:22,007
And that's why the metta practice after vipassana as a daily practice is absolutely necessary.

508
00:44:22,847 --> 00:44:25,791
Otherwise you can become too detached, too disinterested.

509
00:44:26,512 --> 00:44:29,034
And that's what draws you back into relationships.

510
00:44:29,672 --> 00:44:35,268
So make sure that you always do a little, even if it's only a few lines, just to bring you into an attitude.

511
00:44:35,710 --> 00:44:41,806
And then as you get up, you take with you into your daily life the wisdom and the loving kindness that you've just been practicing.

512
00:44:42,509 --> 00:44:44,052
It's a substrate.

513
00:44:46,277 --> 00:44:47,478
And then finally, equanimity.

514
00:44:47,498 --> 00:44:54,387
And I think I've said before, this is the greatest of all virtues because it subsists them all.

515
00:44:54,407 --> 00:44:56,751
It keeps them all balanced, that equanimity.

516
00:44:57,170 --> 00:44:59,092
So that we can practice.

517
00:44:59,614 --> 00:45:02,257
And we lose equanimity when we get too excited.

518
00:45:02,297 --> 00:45:08,724
Every time we fall into an unwholesome state, we've lost equanimity, basically.

519
00:45:09,228 --> 00:45:16,947
Equanimity is that calmness of the heart, steadiness of attention and coming from the place of wisdom.

520
00:45:17,688 --> 00:45:20,757
That's what brings about equanimity.

521
00:45:35,552 --> 00:45:46,621
So there we have it, you see, we find ourselves doing things impulsively, things that we often sometimes regret, things that make us feel embarrassed afterwards.

522
00:45:47,663 --> 00:45:52,835
And what we have to do is recognize that, you know, and then we make that resolution.

523
00:45:54,335 --> 00:46:16,021
and we remind ourselves, and then come the next time, hopefully we've got that clear, calm awareness, carrying all day long this sort of just relaxing into the present moment, and we see that old impulse come, and we've got just that enough space to say no,

524
00:46:16,103 --> 00:46:25,661
in the sense of not doing it, and then to allow that impulse to arise and to slowly pass away, and then for the right intention to arrive.

525
00:46:26,423 --> 00:46:29,550
And then very slowly you get this movement.

526
00:46:30,211 --> 00:46:37,385
And we can surprise ourselves every so often with a spontaneous act which is coming from the heart of wisdom.

527
00:46:40,099 --> 00:46:59,610
So I can only hope, my words have been of some assistance, that your life will become fully happy and spontaneous, leading you towards final liberation, sooner rather than later.

